<BaseLayout title="Sony A7 V vs Canon R6 III — cameraupick" description="Sony A7 V vs Canon R6 III comparison: autofocus, stabilization, rolling shutter, codecs, and who each camera suits.">
<section class="section">
      <h2>TL;DR picks</h2>
      <div class="grid">
        <article class="card" id="canon-r6-iii">
          <div class="tag">Pick</div>
          <h3>Canon R6 III</h3>
          <p>Cleaner rolling shutter, stronger IBIS, great AF for action and handheld video.</p>
          <a href="#" class="btn-buy" rel="sponsored noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"
            style="margin-top:10px; display:inline-block; font-size:14px;">Check Price on Amazon &rarr;</a>
        </article>
        <article class="card" id="sony-a7-v">
          <div class="tag">Runner-up</div>
          <h3>Sony A7 V</h3>
          <p>Massive lens ecosystem, flexible color tools, improved thermals and AF variety.</p>
          <a href="#" class="btn-buy" rel="sponsored noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"
            style="margin-top:10px; display:inline-block; font-size:14px;">Check Price on Amazon &rarr;</a>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <div class="tag">Budget</div>
          <h3>Consider A7 IV / R6 II</h3>
          <p>Still excellent hybrids if you don’t need the latest codecs and rolling shutter gains.</p>
          <a href="#" class="btn-buy" data-product="sony-a7iv" rel="sponsored noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"
            style="margin-top:10px; display:inline-block; font-size:14px;">Check Price on Amazon &rarr;</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Quick comparison</h2>
      <table class="compare-table">
        <tr>
          <th>Category</th>
          <th>Sony A7 V</th>
          <th>Canon R6 III</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Best for</td>
          <td>Hybrid, lens flexibility</td>
          <td>Hybrid/action, handheld video</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Video</td>
          <td>4K60 HQ, 10-bit, better rolling shutter than A7 IV</td>
          <td>4K60 oversampled, strong motion handling</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Stabilization</td>
          <td>IBIS + Active (crop)</td>
          <td>IBIS stronger for handheld</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>AF</td>
          <td>Great subject variety, improved tracking</td>
          <td>Excellent human/animal tracking</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Thermals</td>
          <td>Improved heat handling</td>
          <td>Solid for long takes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Lenses</td>
          <td>Huge E-mount options</td>
          <td>RF lenses pricier, fewer third-party</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Scores</h2>
      <div class="rating-grid">
        <div class="score-card"><span class="score">9.0</span><span class="score-label">Overall (R6 III)</span></div>
        <div class="score-card"><span class="score">8.9</span><span class="score-label">Photo (A7 V)</span></div>
        <div class="score-card"><span class="score">8.7</span><span class="score-label">Video (R6 III)</span></div>
        <div class="score-card"><span class="score">8.6</span><span class="score-label">Value (A7 V)</span></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Key differences</h2>
      <div class="grid">
        <article class="card card-plain">
          <h3>Autofocus</h3>
          <p>Both excellent; Canon is stickier for humans/animals. Sony strong across varied subjects and lenses.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card card-plain">
          <h3>Rolling shutter</h3>
          <p>A7 V improves over A7 IV but R6 III remains cleaner for fast motion and pans.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card card-plain">
          <h3>Stabilization</h3>
          <p>R6 III IBIS better for handheld video; Sony Active helps but crops.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card card-plain">
          <h3>Heat</h3>
          <p>Both improved; Canon still reliable for longer 4K sessions. Sony better than older A7 IV.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card card-plain">
          <h3>Lenses</h3>
          <p>Sony: massive third-party and native options. Canon RF: great glass but pricier, fewer third-party AF
            choices.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Choose Sony A7 V if…</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>You want the deepest lens ecosystem, flexible color options, and improved thermals over A7 IV. Ideal for
          hybrid shooters who mix talking heads, events, and photo work.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Choose Canon R6 III if…</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>You shoot fast-moving subjects, need strong IBIS for handheld video, and want cleaner rolling shutter. Great
          for weddings, documentary, and action hybrids.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Bottom line</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>A7 V wins on lenses and flexibility; R6 III wins on motion handling and IBIS. Pick based on your subjects and
          whether you want lens variety or the cleanest handheld video.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Affiliate note</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>This page may contain affiliate links. If you buy through them, we may earn a small commission at no extra
          cost to you.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

